title: Transcript of Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food on chicken imports
content_text: Following is a transcript of the remarks made by the Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr Yeoh Eng-kiong, at a media session after visiting the Hong Chi Pinehill Advanced Training Centre today (May 18): Reporter: Dr Yeoh, some poultry traders are demanding the Government to increase the number of live chickens to 80, 000 after the next rest day. What do you think of that? Is that reasonable? Dr Yeoh: Well, do you think it is reasonable? I think we have already said that

currently we are maintaining the level of imports at 30, 000 because of the new 
quarantine arrangements, as you know, with the outbreak of the avian influenza 
in the region of such scale which is really very alarming to the global 
community and is very alarming to our Hong Kong community. Because of the new 
quarantine arrangements, which are much more vigorous than before, both the 
Mainland authorities and ourselves have agreed we need to review how these new 
quarantine arrangements are working out first. So for the time being, we are

quarantine arrangements are working out first. So for the time being, we are 
maintaining the level at 30, 000 until we evaluate this situation. But on the 
other side, we have already told the trade that the practices in the past cannot 
continue and if we are going to continue to have live chickens in the territory, 
there must be some changes to the practices. One of the practices that we are 
proposing in the markets is to reduce the density of our stalls in the markets.

proposing in the markets is to reduce the density of our stalls in the markets. 
The objective is to reduce the number of stalls to half so that we will have 
double the amount of space. What we are trying to do is to increase the space 
provision for each stall so that the markets will be less crowded and we can 
improve the hygienic conditions. So as such, we have to have a reduction in the 
number of stalls. So obviously the number of chickens in the markets cannot be

number of stalls. So obviously the number of chickens in the markets cannot be 
increased. Our objective is mainly to improve the hygienic condition by 
increasing the space for each stall and our objective is to double the space for 
each stall. Then we need to look at the number of chickens that need to be
